[
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_PPT_MMAT5390Lecture1_page_023_0",
    "text": "What is a digital image?",
    "canon_role": "section_header",
    "bbox": [
      0.24273256011568603,
      0.038690474960227525,
      0.7151162711888197,
      0.09496124084002516
    ],
    "page": "PPT_MMAT5390Lecture1_page_023",
    "order": 1
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_PPT_MMAT5390Lecture1_page_023_1",
    "text": "Mathematical definition:",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.02761628748348689,
      0.14914021198904887,
      0.4171511620513968,
      0.18419312204195892
    ],
    "page": "PPT_MMAT5390Lecture1_page_023",
    "order": 2
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_PPT_MMAT5390Lecture1_page_023_2",
    "text": "A 2D (grayscale) digital image is a 2D function defined on a 2D domain (usually rectangular domain):",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.07703490333978781,
      0.20138888928342355,
      0.9447674206427704,
      0.27713178301329905
    ],
    "page": "PPT_MMAT5390Lecture1_page_023",
    "order": 3
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_PPT_MMAT5390Lecture1_page_023_3",
    "text": "",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.38292852783203124,
      0.30283085123697917,
      0.5488431396484375,
      0.3497165934244792
    ],
    "page": "PPT_MMAT5390Lecture1_page_023",
    "order": 4
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_PPT_MMAT5390Lecture1_page_023_4",
    "text": "f(x,y) is called the brightness/intensity/grey level;",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.07691394811857079,
      0.38260335264294665,
      0.7254673422545456,
      0.4260882397610086
    ],
    "page": "PPT_MMAT5390Lecture1_page_023",
    "order": 5
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_PPT_MMAT5390Lecture1_page_023_5",
    "text": "(x,y) is the spatial coordinates of the image.",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.0750000173184832,
      0.4332010585620893,
      0.6291666597648498,
      0.4722222225832533
    ],
    "page": "PPT_MMAT5390Lecture1_page_023",
    "order": 6
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_PPT_MMAT5390Lecture1_page_023_6",
    "text": "Thus, a 2D digital image looks like this:",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.07703488158222589,
      0.484457671780635,
      0.5770348815822259,
      0.521317829984406
    ],
    "page": "PPT_MMAT5390Lecture1_page_023",
    "order": 7
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_PPT_MMAT5390Lecture1_page_023_7",
    "text": "",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.23683502451681865,
      0.5405315581327799,
      0.7282305769312751,
      0.7268518512228913
    ],
    "page": "PPT_MMAT5390Lecture1_page_023",
    "order": 8
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_PPT_MMAT5390Lecture1_page_023_8",
    "text": "Each element in the matrix is called pixel (picture element);",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.09738373166997775,
      0.771164020633294,
      0.8139534808057975,
      0.8062169306862041
    ],
    "page": "PPT_MMAT5390Lecture1_page_023",
    "order": 9
  },
  {
    "chunk_id": "docling_PPT_MMAT5390Lecture1_page_023_9",
    "text": "Usually, 0 < f(x, y) <G-1 and (N = 2n , G = 2\")",
    "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
    "bbox": [
      0.07690951379173366,
      0.815782955627908,
      0.7063953476219664,
      0.8608207802687371
    ],
    "page": "PPT_MMAT5390Lecture1_page_023",
    "order": 10
  }
]